  "prompt": "Why don't US representatives run for president?",
  "response": "Actually, many US representatives do run for president. Some notable examples include:\n\n1. John F. Kennedy (Representative before becoming president)\n2. Gerald Ford\n3. Barack Obama (Senator, not a Representative)\n4. Paul Ryan\n5. Dennis Kucinich\n\nHowever, running for president is challenging and requires:\n- Significant financial resources\n- National name recognition\n- Strong political base\n- Time away from congressional duties\n\nRepresentatives often prefer to:\n- Build seniority in Congress\n- Focus on committee work\n- Represent their specific district\n- Run for higher state or Senate offices first\n\nThe House of Representatives is often seen as a stepping stone to higher political offices, including the presidency, but not every representative chooses this path.",
